<div class="markdown"><h1 id="Using-Julia-to-create,-solve,-and-visualize-Pendulum-motion">Using Julia to create, solve, and visualize Pendulum motion</h1><p>In this notebook, with the help of a Microsoft copilot agent, I go through three steps:</p><ol><li><p>define kinetic and potential energy for the Lagrangian</p></li><li><p>create an equation of motion </p></li><li><p>solve and visualize the differential equation</p></li></ol><p>The kinetic and potential energy is determined from the simple pendulum: a point mass attached to a constant-length support. </p><p><img alt="model of the simple pendulum angle is measured from vertical position and gravity is pointing down" src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cooperrc/dynamics/refs/heads/main/images/pendulum.svg"/></p><p>First step is to import packages and define the Lagrangian, </p><p class="tex">$$T = T - V$$</p><p>where</p><p class="tex">$$T = \frac{1}{2}mv^2 = \frac{1}{2}mL^2\dot{\theta}^2$$</p><p>and</p><p class="tex">$$V = mgL(1- \cos\theta)$$</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>using Symbolics, Plots, DifferentialEquations, Latexify, OrdinaryDiffEq</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
@variables t m L g
@variables θ(t)     # θ is a function of time
D = Differential(t) # time derivative operator

# Define kinetic and potential energy
T = (1//2) * m * L^2 * (D(θ))^2
V = m * g * L * (1 - cos(θ))

# Lagrangian
Lag = T - V
end</code></pre>
<p class="tex">$$\begin{equation}
 - L ~ g ~ m ~ \left( 1 - \cos\left( \theta\left( t \right) \right) \right) + \frac{1}{2} ~ \left( \frac{\mathrm{d} ~ \theta\left( t \right)}{\mathrm{d}t} \right)^{2} ~ L^{2} ~ m
\end{equation}$$</p>


<div class="markdown"><h2 id="Create-the-equation-of-motion">Create the equation of motion</h2><p>Next, since the Lagrangian, <code>Lag</code> is a symbolic math term, I use <code>Symbolics</code> to find the partial and full derivatives for the Lagrangian equation of motion, </p><p class="tex">$$\frac{d}{dt}\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial \dot{\theta}}\right) - \frac{\partial L}{\partial \theta} =\frac{\delta L}{\delta \theta}$$</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
dL_dθdot = Symbolics.derivative(Lag, D(θ))
dL_dθ    = Symbolics.derivative(Lag, θ)

EL_equation = expand_derivatives(D(dL_dθdot) - dL_dθ)
end</code></pre>
<p class="tex">$$\begin{equation}
L^{2} ~ m ~ \frac{\mathrm{d}^{2} ~ \theta\left( t \right)}{\mathrm{d}t^{2}} + L ~ g ~ m ~ \sin\left( \theta\left( t \right) \right)
\end{equation}$$</p>


<div class="markdown"><h2 id="Lagrange-equation-of-motion">Lagrange equation of motion</h2><p>The equation of motion for dynamic systems is usually, </p><p class="tex">$$\ddot{q} = f(q,~\dot{q},~t)$$</p><p>or in this case, </p><p class="tex">$$\ddot{\theta} = f(\theta)$$</p><p>I create the <code>ode_symbolic</code> variable that solves for the acceleration term, <span class="tex">\(\ddot{\theta}\)</span>. </p><p>Then, I use the <code>build_function</code> to create a Julia function, <code>θ_double_dot</code> that calculates the acceleration given inputs for <code>θ, D(θ), g, L</code>: angle, angular velocity, gravity, and length, respectively.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>ode_symbolic = solve_for(EL_equation, D(D(θ)))# isolate θ̈ symbolically</code></pre>
<p class="tex">$$\begin{equation}
\frac{ - g ~ \sin\left( \theta\left( t \right) \right)}{L}
\end{equation}$$</p>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
#θ̈_expr = ode_symbolic[D(D(θ))]# extract θ̈(θ)

θ_double_dot = build_function(ode_symbolic, θ, D(θ), g, L; expression=Val(false))
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h2 id="Visualize-the-Results">Visualize the Results</h2><p>Now, the cool result. I use the <code>Plots</code> package and the <code>@gif</code> command to </p><ol><li><p>plot the angle and angular velocity vs time</p></li><li><p>create an animation of the angle+velocity synced to the motion of the pendulum</p></li></ol><p>First, <code>ODEProblem</code> solves the initial value problem. Then, <code>@gif</code> uses a for-loop to cycle through the values and positions of the pendulum at each time step. The result is a repeating animation of the positions and velocities all in sync.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin

# This block defines the numerical pendulum ODE and solves it
# θ_state = [θ; θ̇]

function pendulum_ode!(dstate, state, p, t)
    position_angle   = state[1]
    velocity_angle   = state[2]

    g, L = p
    dstate[1] = velocity_angle
    dstate[2] = θ_double_dot(position_angle, velocity_angle, g, L)
end

initial_state = [30*pi/180, 0.0]   # 30-deg initial displacement
parameters    = (9.81, 1.0) # g, L
time_span     = (0.0, 6.0)

prob = ODEProblem(pendulum_ode!, initial_state, time_span, parameters)
sol = solve(prob, reltol = 0.000001)
end</code></pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>begin
# Animation with three panels: θ(t), ω(t), and pendulum motion
# Packages referenced: Plots.jl, DifferentialEquations.jl
gravity_value, length_pendulum = parameters
number_frames = 150; origin_pivot = (0.0, 0.0)
time_values = range(time_span[1], time_span[2], length=number_frames)

@gif for time_value in time_values
    current_state = sol(time_value)
    angle_current, speed_current = current_state[1], current_state[2]

    angle_plot = plot(sol.t, sol[1,:], xlabel="time (s)", ylabel="θ (rad)", title="Angle vs Time", legend=false)
    scatter!(angle_plot, [time_value], [angle_current])

    speed_plot = plot(sol.t, sol[2,:], xlabel="time (s)", ylabel="ω (rad/s)", title="Angular Speed vs Time", legend=false)
    scatter!(speed_plot, [time_value], [speed_current])

    bob_position_x = length_pendulum * sin(angle_current)
    bob_position_y = -length_pendulum * cos(angle_current)

    pendulum_plot = plot(xlim=(-1.2length_pendulum, 1.2length_pendulum), ylim=(-1.2length_pendulum, 0.2length_pendulum),
                         aspect_ratio=:equal, xlabel="x (m)", ylabel="y (m)", title="Pendulum Motion", legend=false)
    plot!(pendulum_plot, [origin_pivot[1], bob_position_x], [origin_pivot[2], bob_position_y], lw=3)
    scatter!(pendulum_plot, [bob_position_x], [bob_position_y], ms=8)

    plot(angle_plot, speed_plot, pendulum_plot, layout=@layout([a; b; c]), size=(700,900))
end every 2
end</code></pre>
